#compdef minizinc
# =============================================================================
# minizinc — Monash University + NICTA's "MiniZinc constraint
#             modeling language driver" — a high-level
#             CONSTRAINT MODELING LANGUAGE + COMPILER for
#             combinatorial optimization + satisfaction
#             problems.  MiniZinc programs declare:
#               - DECISION VARIABLES with finite domains
#               - CONSTRAINTS over those variables
#               - OBJECTIVE FUNCTION (for optimization) or
#                 satisfy-only goal
#             The `minizinc` driver compiles .mzn (MiniZinc)
#             source to .fzn (FlatZinc — a low-level
#             solver-independent representation), then
#             DISPATCHES to a configured backend solver
#             (Gecode / Chuffed / OR-tools / Picat / G12 /
#             Choco / CPLEX / Gurobi / scop3 / etc).
#             Distinguishing features:
#               - HIGH-LEVEL ALGEBRAIC notation for
#                 combinatorial problems (n-queens, knapsack,
#                 graph coloring, scheduling, vehicle routing,
#                 cryptarithmetic, etc)
#               - GLOBAL CONSTRAINTS as language primitives
#                 (alldifferent, circuit, count, regular,
#                 element, table, lex_less, etc) — provided
#                 by MiniZinc stdlib
#               - SOLVER-INDEPENDENT MODELING (one .mzn model
#                 runs on 12+ different backend solvers)
#               - INTERMEDIATE OUTPUT support for
#                 long-running optimization (--intermediate-
#                 solutions emits each improving solution)
#               - JSON STREAMING (--json-stream) for IDE/
#                 tooling integration
#             Used in operations research, supply chain
#             planning, scheduling, automated planning, AI
#             constraint solving research.  MiniZinc was
#             developed at NICTA (National ICT Australia) +
#             Monash University as the successor to OPL and
#             the AMPL/CPLEX modeling traditions.
#
# Author:  Guido Tack (Monash University) + Gleb Belov +
#          Peter Stuckey + Mark Wallace + NICTA team —
#          MiniZinc since 2007 (initial release).  Core
#          development at Monash University's School of
#          Information Technology, with international
#          academic contributions.  Annual MiniZinc Challenge
#          (since 2008) showcases solver performance on
#          benchmark problems.
# Source:  https://github.com/MiniZinc/libminizinc
#          https://github.com/MiniZinc/libminizinc/blob/master/minizinc.cpp
#          https://github.com/MiniZinc/libminizinc/blob/master/lib/solver.cpp
# CLI:     minizinc.cpp + lib/solver.cpp — written in C++.
#          Hand-rolled argv processing through MznSolver class
#          consuming a `std::vector<std::string> args`.  No
#          external CLI library — uses the MiniZinc SolverFactory
#          + Options system to dispatch flags to per-solver
#          backend plugins.
# Library: MiniZinc-native SolverFactory + Options system
#          (MiniZinc has its own internal CLI option system
#           tied to the MULTI-BACKEND-SOLVER architecture:
#           each registered SolverFactory contributes
#           solver-specific flags through a registration
#           system, and the driver's argv parser dispatches
#           the relevant subset of flags to each solver's
#           factory based on which backend is selected via
#           --solver.  This is FUNDAMENTALLY DIFFERENT from
#           the typical argv-as-flat-table model — MiniZinc's
#           argv is PARTITIONED across multiple solver
#           subsystems at runtime based on solver selection.)
# License: MPL-2.0 (libminizinc + MiniZinc IDE)
# Status:  MiniZinc — 686+ stars on MiniZinc/libminizinc
#          (compiler), 173+ stars on MiniZinc/MiniZincIDE,
#          active development at Monash University.
#          Annual MiniZinc Challenge competition runs since
#          2008 with solver vendors competing on benchmark
#          problems.  Industrial users include logistics
#          companies, manufacturing planners, airlines,
#          academic researchers.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 83RD LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy welcomes
# its 83RD DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE — MINIZINC (Monash University + NICTA,
# 2007-present) — and its FIRST documented MiniZinc CLI mechanism:
# the MULTI-BACKEND SolverFactory + Options registration system that
# DISPATCHES argv across multiple solver subsystems based on the
# selected backend.
# Taxonomy now spans 340 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 83 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R598 Rust=57 anyhow/sdf → R599 Go=57 aurora/
# imgdiff → R600 TS-Node=57 boxen/wtfjs THE 600-MILESTONE) followed by
# 1 NEW LANGUAGE (R601 MiniZinc THIS).  Leaderboard unchanged:
# Rust=57, Go=57, TypeScript-Node=57 (three-way tie at 57 since R600).
#
# MiniZinc is DISTINCT from every other documented language by being
# the CANONICAL CONSTRAINT PROGRAMMING (CP) MODELING LANGUAGE — the
# language that operations researchers + AI planning researchers use
# to specify combinatorial optimization problems independent of any
# specific solver.  Compare:
#   - Souffle (Datalog dialect, in corpus) — declarative logic for
#     program analysis
#   - Clingo (Potassco ASP, in corpus) — answer set programming
#   - DLV (in corpus) — disjunctive Datalog with stable model
#     semantics
#   - Mercury (in corpus) — purely declarative logic+functional
#   - Picat (in corpus) — multi-paradigm logic+constraint
#   - Curry (in corpus via pakcs) — functional + logic
#   - SWI-Prolog (in corpus via plwm) — Prolog with CLP libraries
#   - MiniZinc (R601 THIS) — CONSTRAINT PROGRAMMING modeling
#     language with SOLVER-AGNOSTIC compilation to FlatZinc
#
# MiniZinc occupies the "specify CP problems abstractly" niche,
# distinct from each of the other logic-programming entries that
# focus on either:
#   - INFERENCE (Datalog/ASP/Prolog) for query answering
#   - PROGRAM ANALYSIS (Souffle) for compiler/security tools
#   - DECLARATIVE COMPUTATION (Mercury/Curry) general-purpose
# MiniZinc specifically targets OPTIMIZATION + SATISFACTION over
# finite-domain variables — the IBM ILOG OPL + AMPL traditional
# OR space.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS MINIZINC AND WHY IS IT THE 83RD LANGUAGE?
#
# MiniZinc is a declarative constraint modeling language for
# combinatorial optimization + satisfaction problems.
# Distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. HIGH-LEVEL ALGEBRAIC NOTATION — MiniZinc programs read
#      like mathematical specifications:
#
#          % N-Queens problem in MiniZinc
#          int: n = 8;
#          array[1..n] of var 1..n: q;
#
#          constraint alldifferent(q);
#          constraint alldifferent([q[i] + i | i in 1..n]);
#          constraint alldifferent([q[i] - i | i in 1..n]);
#
#          solve satisfy;
#
#          output [show(q[i]) ++ " " | i in 1..n] ++ ["\n"];
#
#      The `alldifferent` is a GLOBAL CONSTRAINT (a primitive
#      in MiniZinc's stdlib).  Compare:
#         * Prolog: backtracking search with CLP(FD) library
#         * SWI-Prolog: clp(Z) module for integer constraints
#         * OPL (IBM ILOG): commercial CP modeling language
#         * AMPL: mathematical programming language (LP-focused)
#         * MiniZinc: HIGH-LEVEL DECLARATIVE specification of
#                      constraints + objective; SOLVER-AGNOSTIC
#      FIRST documented language with high-level constraint
#      modeling + solver-agnostic compilation in the taxonomy.
#
#   2. GLOBAL CONSTRAINTS AS PRIMITIVES — MiniZinc's standard
#      library includes ~100 global constraints that are
#      RECOGNIZED by solvers + DECOMPOSED appropriately for
#      each backend:
#         * alldifferent(array) — all values distinct
#         * circuit(array) — array forms Hamiltonian cycle
#         * count(array, value, count) — count occurrences
#         * regular(array, dfa-spec) — matches DFA language
#         * element(array, idx, val) — array indexing constraint
#         * table(array, table-of-tuples) — value-tuple membership
#         * lex_less(a, b) — lexicographic ordering
#         * cumulative(start, dur, res, capacity) — scheduling
#         * bin_packing(bins, weights, capacities) — bin packing
#         * disjoint(intervals) — intervals don't overlap
#         * subset(set-a, set-b) — set inclusion
#         * (and ~90 more)
#      Each global is decomposed differently per backend solver
#      — Gecode handles alldifferent with its native propagator,
#      Chuffed with SAT-based propagation, OR-tools with its
#      built-in alldiff, etc.  Compare:
#         * Prolog/CLP(FD): library-level constraints (not
#                            language-level)
#         * OPL: similar global constraints
#         * MiniZinc: ~100 GLOBAL CONSTRAINTS as stdlib primitives
#      FIRST documented language with 100+ global constraints
#      as language-level stdlib.
#
#   3. SOLVER-AGNOSTIC COMPILATION TO FLATZINC — MiniZinc
#      compiles .mzn → .fzn (FlatZinc, a low-level
#      solver-input format).  Each backend solver reads
#      FlatZinc + produces solutions.  Currently supported
#      backends:
#         * Gecode (Christian Schulte, KTH) — CP search
#         * Chuffed (Geoffrey Chu, Monash) — lazy clause
#                                              generation
#         * OR-tools (Google) — CP-SAT solver
#         * Picat (Picat dev team) — multi-paradigm
#         * G12 (NICTA G12 platform — legacy)
#         * Choco (Choco team, Nantes) — Java CP solver
#         * SICStus Prolog — Prolog with CLP(FD)
#         * CPLEX (IBM, commercial)
#         * Gurobi (Gurobi, commercial)
#         * Cbc (COIN-OR open-source MIP)
#         * SCIP (ZIB, German academic MIP)
#         * Yuck (CP), MiniSAT (SAT), and others
#      One .mzn problem runs on any backend just by changing
#      `--solver`.  Compare:
#         * OPL: tied to IBM CPLEX
#         * AMPL: tied to LP/MIP solvers
#         * Prolog: solver IS the language
#         * MiniZinc: 12+ INTERCHANGEABLE backends
#      FIRST documented language with 12+ backend-solver
#      interchangeability as core design.
#
#   4. ANNUAL MINIZINC CHALLENGE — Since 2008, the MiniZinc
#      Challenge has run annually as a constraint-solving
#      benchmark competition.  Solver vendors submit their
#      backends; the same MiniZinc problems are run on each;
#      gold/silver/bronze medals are awarded.  This has
#      driven SUBSTANTIAL PROGRESS in CP solver performance
#      over 15+ years (winners include Chuffed multiple
#      times, OR-tools, Picat, Gecode-style propagators).
#      Compare every other documented language — none have
#      a 15+ year continuous benchmark competition driving
#      ecosystem progress.  FIRST documented language with
#      continuous-benchmark-competition ecosystem-progress
#      driver.
#
#   5. ACADEMIC + INDUSTRIAL DEPLOYMENT — MiniZinc is the
#      teaching language of choice for constraint programming
#      courses at major universities (MIT, Stanford, ETH
#      Zurich, KTH, etc).  Industrial users include:
#         * Logistics companies (route planning, vehicle
#           dispatch)
#         * Manufacturing (production scheduling, machine
#           assignment)
#         * Airlines (crew rostering, aircraft routing)
#         * Healthcare (nurse scheduling, OR scheduling)
#         * Education (timetabling, exam scheduling)
#         * Sports (league scheduling)
#         * AI planning research (PDDL alternative)
#      Compare:
#         * OPL: IBM-tied industrial usage
#         * AMPL: math programming usage
#         * MiniZinc: BROADLY-ADOPTED in academia + industry
#                      with cross-vendor solver competition
#      FIRST documented language with academic-teaching +
#      industrial-deployment + competition-driven progress
#      coverage.
#
# Use cases for MiniZinc:
#   * Combinatorial optimization (knapsack, bin packing, TSP)
#   * Scheduling (job shop, project scheduling, RCPSP)
#   * Resource allocation (room assignment, vehicle routing)
#   * Configuration (product configuration, decision support)
#   * Cryptography (CP-based key search, cipher analysis)
#   * Bioinformatics (RNA folding, sequence alignment)
#   * Game playing (Sudoku solver, n-queens, magic squares)
#   * Teaching CP fundamentals + OR techniques
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE minizinc CLI — MULTI-BACKEND SolverFactory + Options
#                     registration system
#
# minizinc's argv processing is in lib/solver.cpp via the
# MznSolver class.  The dispatch architecture:
#
#     int run(const std::string& exe,
#             const std::vector<std::string>& args,
#             bool jsonStream) {
#         try {
#             Timer startTime;
#             MznSolver slv(std::cout, std::cerr, startTime);
#             slv.run(args, "", exe);
#         } catch (...) { ... }
#     }
#
#     // The MznSolver.run() iterates through args and
#     // dispatches to:
#     //   - Driver-level flags (compiler options)
#     //   - Flattener-level flags (FlatZinc generation)
#     //   - Solver-level flags (PER-BACKEND solver options)
#     //
#     // Each SolverFactory registers its supported flags via:
#     //   factory.registerFlag("--gecode-restart", ...)
#     //   factory.registerFlag("--chuffed-laziness", ...)
#     //   factory.registerFlag("--ortools-num-workers", ...)
#     //
#     // The driver routes each argv element to the appropriate
#     // subsystem based on PREFIX MATCHING or REGISTERED FLAG
#     // ATTRIBUTION.
#
# Driver flags + flattener flags + solver-selection flags:
#
#   --help                   Show help
#   --version                Show version
#   --solvers, --solvers-json  List available solvers
#   --solver <id>            Select backend solver
#   --solver-json <json>     Inline solver configuration
#   --time-limit <ms>        Overall time limit in milliseconds
#   --solver-time-limit <ms> Solver-specific time limit
#   --statistics, -s         Print solver statistics
#   --solver-statistics      Print solver-specific statistics
#   --compiler-statistics    Print compiler statistics
#   --intermediate, -i       Print intermediate solutions
#   --intermediate-solutions Same as -i
#   --no-intermediate        Disable intermediate solutions
#   --all-satisfaction, -a   Find all satisfaction solutions
#   --random-seed, --seed <n>  Random seed for solver
#   --verbose, -v            Verbose output
#   --verbose-compilation    Verbose compiler output
#   --verbose-solving        Verbose solver output
#   --json-stream            JSON-streaming output mode
#   --keep-paths             Keep multi-pass file paths
#   --param-file <file>      Read parameter file
#   --stdlib-dir <dir>       Stdlib directory override
#   --config-dirs            List config directories
#   --compile, -c            Compile only (.mzn → .fzn)
#   --ozn-file <file>        Output ozn file
#   -I <dir>                 Include directory
#   -G <stdlib>              Use specified stdlib variant
#   -m <model>               Model file
#   -d <data>                Data file
#   -t <ms>                  Time limit shortcut
#   -n-i                     No intermediate
#
# Plus per-backend flags (Gecode, Chuffed, OR-tools, etc) that
# get partitioned based on selected --solver.
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented CLI parser:
#
#   1. MULTI-BACKEND SOLVERFACTORY DISPATCH — Every other
#      documented argv parser has flat option tables.  MiniZinc's
#      argv is PARTITIONED across multiple solver subsystems
#      based on --solver selection.
#
#   2. CONSTRAINT-MODELING-LANGUAGE INVOCATION — Every other
#      documented compiler emits machine code or bytecode.
#      MiniZinc compiles to FlatZinc (an intermediate format)
#      and then dispatches to a backend solver process.
#
#   3. 12+ BACKEND-SOLVER INTERCHANGEABILITY — Every other
#      documented compiler is monolithic.  MiniZinc supports
#      12+ interchangeable backend solvers via --solver.
#
#   4. GLOBAL-CONSTRAINT STDLIB AS LANGUAGE PRIMITIVES — Every
#      other documented compiler has fixed semantics.  MiniZinc
#      stdlib provides ~100 global constraints as language-level
#      primitives that backend solvers can decompose differently.
#
#   5. 17-YEAR CONTINUOUS-COMPETITION ECOSYSTEM — Every other
#      documented language ecosystem lacks formal benchmark
#      competition.  MiniZinc Challenge runs annually 2008-
#      present driving solver-vendor progress.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/MiniZinc/libminizinc/blob/master/lib/solver.cpp
# `printUsage` function + argv-dispatch logic in MznSolver class.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)--version[show version]' \
    '(- *)--solvers[list available backend solvers]' \
    '(- *)--solvers-json[list backend solvers as JSON]' \
    '(- *)--config-dirs[list MiniZinc config directories]' \
    '--solver=[select backend solver]:solver:(gecode chuffed cbc cplex gurobi or-tools scip choco picat g12 sicstus minisat yuck)' \
    '--solver-json=[inline JSON solver configuration]:json:' \
    '--time-limit=[overall time limit (ms)]:ms:' \
    '--solver-time-limit=[solver-specific time limit (ms)]:ms:' \
    '(-t)-t+[time limit shortcut (ms)]:ms:' \
    '(-s --statistics)'{-s,--statistics}'[print solver statistics]' \
    '--solver-statistics[print solver-specific statistics]' \
    '--compiler-statistics[print compiler statistics]' \
    '(-i --intermediate --intermediate-solutions)'{-i,--intermediate,--intermediate-solutions}'[print intermediate (improving) solutions]' \
    '--no-intermediate[disable intermediate solutions]' \
    '--no-intermediate-solutions[disable intermediate solutions]' \
    '(-a --all-satisfaction)'{-a,--all-satisfaction}'[find all satisfaction solutions]' \
    '--disable-all-satisfaction[disable finding all satisfaction solutions]' \
    '(--random-seed --seed)'{--random-seed=,--seed=}'[random seed]:N:' \
    '(-v --verbose)'{-v,--verbose}'[verbose output]' \
    '--verbose-compilation[verbose compiler output]' \
    '--verbose-solving[verbose solver output]' \
    '--json-stream[JSON-streaming output mode]' \
    '--keep-paths[keep multi-pass file paths]' \
    '--param-file=[read parameter file]:file:_files -g "*.json"' \
    '--param-file-no-push=[parameter file (no working-dir push)]:file:_files' \
    '--push-working-directory=[push working directory]:dir:_directories' \
    '--pop-working-directory[pop working directory]' \
    '--stdlib-dir=[stdlib directory override]:dir:_directories' \
    '(-c --compile)'{-c,--compile}'[compile only (emit .fzn)]' \
    '--compile-solution-checker[compile solution checker]' \
    '--ozn-file=[output ozn file]:file:_files -g "*.ozn"' \
    '*-I+[include directory]:dir:_directories' \
    '-G+[use specified stdlib variant]:variant:' \
    '*-m+[model file]:file:_files -g "*.mzn"' \
    '*-d+[data file]:file:_files -g "*.dzn"' \
    '-n-i[no intermediate solutions (legacy)]' \
    '*--mzn-flag=[pass flag to mzn2fzn]:flag:' \
    '*--mzn-flags=[pass flags string to mzn2fzn]:flags:' \
    '*--fzn-flag=[pass flag to FlatZinc backend]:flag:' \
    '*--fzn-flags=[pass flags string to FlatZinc backend]:flags:' \
    '--fzn-cmd=[FlatZinc backend executable]:command:_command_names' \
    '--flatzinc-cmd=[alias for --fzn-cmd]:command:_command_names' \
    '--fzn-needs-paths[FlatZinc backend needs path info]' \
    '--fzn-output-passthrough[pass FlatZinc output through]' \
    '--fzn-time-limit=[FlatZinc backend time limit]:ms:' \
    '*--nl-cmd=[NL backend command]:command:_command_names' \
    '*--nl-flag=[pass flag to NL backend]:flag:' \
    '*--nl-flags=[pass flags string to NL backend]:flags:' \
    '*--backend-flag=[pass flag to backend solver]:flag:' \
    '*--backend-flags=[pass flags string to backend solver]:flags:' \
    '--minizinc-exe=[minizinc executable for child processes]:file:_files' \
    '--only-sections=[only emit specified sections]:sections:' \
    '--not-sections=[exclude specified sections]:sections:' \
    '*:MiniZinc model or data file:_files -g "*.(mzn|dzn|fzn)"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
